         Customer Segmentation & Market Basket Analysis
Application of Data Mining Techniques on E-commerce Data

          Project Overview

This project applies data mining techniques to analyze customer purchasing behaviour using a real-world e-commerce dataset. The goal is to extract meaningful insights that support data-driven decision-making in online retail.

The project focuses on two main tasks:

Customer Segmentation using RFM analysis and K-Means clustering
Market Basket Analysis using the Apriori algorithm to discover product associations

        Dataset
Source: Kaggle E-commerce Dataset
Time Period: December 2010 – December 2011
Initial Records: 541,909 transactions

After preprocessing:

Clean Records: 391,283
Customers: 4,334
Products: 3,660
Total Revenue: £8.74M
 Data Preprocessing

The dataset was cleaned using a structured pipeline:

Removal of missing Customer IDs
 duplicate records
Filtering invalid quantities and prices
Removal of cancelled transactions
Exclusion of non-product entries
 Customer Segmentation (RFM + K-Means)
 RFM Features
Recency – Days since last purchase
Frequency – Number of transactions
Monetary – Total spending
 Clustering
      Algorithm: K-Means
Optimal Clusters: K = 4
Silhouette Score: 0.47
 Customer Segments
 Champions (High Value)
 Loyal Customers
 At-Risk Customers
 Inactive Customers
 Validation
Logistic Regression Accuracy: 99.54%
Random Forest Accuracy: 98.85%
 Market Basket Analysis (Apriori)
Minimum Support: 0.02
Minimum Confidence: 0.50
Minimum Lift: 2.0

         Results
Extracted 30 strong association rules
Strongest product relationship:
Regency Teacup & Saucer variants
Lift: 24.11
 Insights
Customers tend to buy product variants together
Strong opportunities for:
Cross-selling
Product bundling
Recommendation systems

              Key Insights
A small group of customers generates most revenue
Customer behaviour is highly skewed (Pareto principle)
Product associations reveal strong purchasing patterns
Data mining enables targeted marketing strategies

